Question 1

1a: What patterns do you see in the distribution of house prices? (10 pts)

4 points for working code and readable figure

6 points for written response to the prompt

  • could mention the range of prices observed, where the bulk of the distribution is, skew, etc.
# pricing histogram with custom labels and theme
HousePrices %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=price)) +
  geom_histogram(
    fill = "#2D4F67", # Set a custom color by hex code
    binwidth = 7000   # set a custom width of the bars
    ) +
  labs( # set custom labels for title, x axis, and y axis
    title = "Windsor Canada Housing Price Distribution",
    subtitle = "Data from Anglin and Gencay (1996)",
    x = "Sale Price",
    y = "Number of Houses"
  ) +
  theme( # center title text
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
    )

1b: Describe the variable you chose. What are the units? Is it continuous or discrete? (6 pts)

  • Answer will depend on variable chosen. lotsize is the only variable which describes a continuous measure (area), bedrooms, bathrooms, stories, garage, are all integer values representing counts of each type of space. recreation, fullbase, gasheat, aircon, prefer, are all qualitative which take on binary value 'yes' (or 'no') in the presence (or absence) of each type of house attribute.

Example with the continuous variable, lotsize:

HousePrices %>%
  ggplot(aes( x = lotsize, y = price )) +
  geom_point(color = "#2D4F67") + # set custom dot color
  labs( # set custom labels for title, x axis, and y axis
    title = "Houses' Lot Size vs. Sale Price",
    x = "Lot Size (square feet)",
    y = "Sale Price"
  ) +
  theme( plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5) ) # center title text

Example with a discrete variable, bedrooms:

library(ggridges)
HousePrices %>%
  ggplot(aes( x = price, y = as.factor(bedrooms) )) +
  ggridges::geom_density_ridges(aes( fill = bedrooms )) +
  labs( # set custom labels for title, x axis, and y axis
    title = "Houses' Lot Size vs. Number of Bedrooms",
    x = "Sale Price",
    y = "Bedrooms",
  ) +
  theme( plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5) ) + # center title text
  guides( fill = "none" )

1c: Describe some patterns you see in the plot above between price and your chosen variable. (10 pts)

4 points for working code and readable figure

6 points for written response to the prompt

  • For the examples above,

    • lotsize appears to correlate positively to price. As either lotsize or price increase, the points get more spread out which may indicate some evidence of heteroskedasticity.

    • Houses Size vs.Number of Bedrooms plot shows different pricing that the pricing distribution depends on the number of bedrooms. Houses with 3, 4, or 5 bedrooms seem to sell for more on average than 2 bedroom houses. The right tail is also fatter in the distributions with more bedrooms. Relatively few of the two bedroom houses sell for more than six figures, but its not uncommon for a 5 bedroom house to sell for at least that much.

Question 2

2a: Write out a regression model mathematically with price as the dependent variable and the same independent variable you used above: (8 pts)

\[ \text{price}_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{bedrooms}_i + u_i \]

2 points for each component:

  • \(\beta_0\) (or some other variable to represent an intercept)
  • \(\beta_1\) (or some other variable to represent a slope)
  • \(bedrooms_i\) should be replaced by the same variable chosen in Q1
  • \(u_i\) (or other variable to represent error, should be indexed by \(i\))

2b: Now write out a hypothesis test that the regression above will be used to test (6 pts)

\[ H_0: \beta_1 = 0 \\ H_1: \beta_1 \neq 0 \]

Could also be written out in words using the choice of variable:

\[ H_0: \text{The number of bedrooms is unrelated to price} \\ H_1: \text{Number of bedrooms correlates with price} \]

  • Should be a two-tailed test if default lm output is used later

2c: Run your hypothesis test at the 95% significance level. Interpret your results (12 pts)

6 points for correct model and working code

6 points for written interpretation

# save lm model as a named object
model1 <- lm(data = HousePrices, price ~ bedrooms) %>% 
  tidy() # tidy the regression output into an easy to read tibble
model1
term estimate std.error statistic p.value
(Intercept) 28773 4414 6.5 0
bedrooms 13270 1445 9.2 0

For every additional bedroom in a house, the sale price is expected to increase by $13269.98.

The \(t\)-statistic for the two-tailed hypothesis test in question 2b is 9.19 which is greater than the critical value of 1.65. Therefore, we can reject null hypothesis that the number of bedrooms is unrelated to the price of a house.

Question 3

3a: Write out your regression model from 2a but with an additional explanatory variable (8 pts)

\[ \text{price}_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1\text{bedrooms}_i + \beta_2\text{lotsize}_i + u_i \]

3b: Run this regression and report your results (12 pts)

6 points for correct model and working code

6 points for written interpretation

model2 <- lm(data = HousePrices, price ~ bedrooms + lotsize) %>% 
  tidy() # tidy the regression output into an easy to read tibble
model2
term estimate std.error statistic p.value
(Intercept) 5613 4102.82 1.4 0.17
bedrooms 10567 1247.68 8.5 0.00
lotsize 6 0.42 14.3 0.00

For two houses on equally sized lots, the house with one more bedroom is expected to sell for $10567.35 more. When holding the number of bedrooms constant, the expected increase in price for each additional square foot of lot size is $6.05. For a house on a zero square-foot lot with zero bedrooms, the estimated price is $5612.6.

The \(t\)-statistic for the two-tailed hypothesis test in question 3a is 8.47 which is greater than the critical value of 1.65. Therefore, we can reject null hypothesis that the number of bedrooms is unrelated to the price of a house.

  • This estimate of \(\beta_1\) is lower than the estimate in model1. It is likely that lotsize positively correlates with both price and bedrooms because larger houses tend to have larger lots, more bedrooms, and higher prices. That would upward bias our \(\beta_1\) estimate from model1, so it makes sense that when we control for lotsize in model2, our estimated slope decreases. The standard error around \(\beta_1\) is also lower in model2 because some of the previously unexplained variation in price is now being explained by lotsize.

  • The \(R^2\) increases from 0.13 in model1 to 0.37 in model2. This is unsurprising because model2 includes more information about a house, specifically lot size. The additional variation in price explained by adding in lotsize as measured by \(R^2\) is 0.24, while the difference in adjusted \(R^2\) is 0.24. This indicates that the mechanical increases in \(R^2\) from one additional variable is not substantial.

Question 4

\[ \begin{align} \text{price}_i = & \beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{lotsize}_i + \beta_2 \text{bedrooms}_i + \\ & \beta_3 \text{bathrooms}_i + \beta_4 \text{stories}_i + \beta_5 \text{driveway}_i + \\ & \beta_6 \text{recreation}_i + \beta_7 \text{fullbase}_i + \beta_8 \text{gasheat}_i + \\ & \beta_9 \text{aircon}_i + \beta_{10} \text{garage}_i + \beta_{11} \text{prefer}_i + u_i \end{align} \]

4a: Run the full model and interpret the \(\beta\) on the same variable you chose in 1b (18 pts)

6 points for correct model and working code

model3 <- lm(
  data = HousePrices, 
  price ~ bedrooms + lotsize + bathrooms + stories + driveway + recreation +
    fullbase + gasheat + aircon + garage + prefer
  ) %>% 
  tidy() # tidy the regression output into an easy to read tibble
model3

8 points for addressing the slope estimate and standard error

When holding all other characteristics of a house constant, the expected increase in price now becomes $1832. This is lower than previous estimates of \(\beta_1\), and although the standard error has also decrease to se_1, we can no longer reject the null hypothesis that price correlates with bedrooms at the 95% confidence level when fully taking into account all other characteristics of a house.

4 points for addressing \(R^2\) and adjusted \(R^2\)

The \(R^2\) value from the full regression is 0.67 and the adjusted \(R^2\) is 0.67.
